  "prompt": "Were humans ever subject to natural selection?",
  "response": "Yes, humans have been subject to natural selection throughout their evolutionary history. Natural selection is the process by which certain traits that increase an individual's ability to survive and reproduce are passed down to future generations, leading to evolution over time.\n\nIn the early stages of human evolution, natural selection played a significant role in shaping the species. Factors such as climate, diet, and predation pressures influenced which traits were advantageous for survival and reproduction. For example, bipedalism (walking on two legs) is thought to have provided early humans with advantages in terms of freeing up their hands for tool use, increasing their ability to see over long distances, and improving their ability to regulate body temperature.\n\nEven as humans developed more advanced societies and technologies, natural selection has continued to influence human evolution, albeit in different ways. For instance, the development of agriculture and the resulting changes in diet led to natural selection favoring individuals with genetic adaptations that allowed them to better digest certain foods, such as lactose in milk.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that in modern times, the influence of natural selection on humans has likely diminished due to advances in medicine, technology, and social structures that have reduced the impact of many selective pressures. Nonetheless, natural selection still occurs, albeit at a slower pace and with different factors at play compared to earlier stages of human evolution.",
